                    <desc>The text opens with a quote found in several sūtras known as the “ye dharma”: “Those phenomena that arise from causes have a cause as well as a cessation,
            The Tathāgata himself spoke this; Thus, spoke the great ascetic.” (chos rnams gang dag rgyus byung de dag ni, rgyu dang de la 'gog pa gang yin pa, de bzhin gshegs pa nyid kyis bka' stsal
            pa, de skad gsungs pa'i tshul can dge sbyong che,). The text then proceeds to describe those phenomena in seven categories that appear to be a condensed form of the twelve links:
            consciousness (rnam par shes pa), name (ming), form (gzugs), six sense sources (skye mched drug), contact (reg pa), feeling (tshor ba), birth (skye ba), and old age and death (rga
            shi).</desc>
